1
00:00:01,161 --> 00:00:08,750
Tonight I want to look at the teaching known as the Destruction of Craving, the Mahatana Sankhya Sutta.

2
00:00:10,250 --> 00:00:27,708
The teaching is given because one of the Buddha's monks, Sati, believes that there is just this one consciousness that runs throughout all our life and was with us in our previous lives and will accompany us throughout our future lives.

3
00:00:28,600 --> 00:00:35,332
Just this one and no other, he claims, thinking he's teaching the Dhamma correctly and according to the Buddha.

4
00:00:36,814 --> 00:00:44,549
The other disciples try to dissuade him, but Sati insists on his view and is summoned by the Buddha to discuss the matter.

5
00:00:47,162 --> 00:00:52,213
The Buddha starts by asking Sati about his one consciousness understanding.

6
00:00:53,234 --> 00:00:58,564
And when Sati repeats this, the Buddha then asks him to define consciousness.

7
00:00:59,908 --> 00:01:09,947
Sati says, it is that which speaks and feels and experiences here and there the results of good and bad actions.

8
00:01:11,192 --> 00:01:20,944
To Sati's dismay, the Buddha dismisses this vehemently, saying, Misguided man, to whom have you ever heard me explain the Dhamma thus?

9
00:01:22,185 --> 00:01:36,721
Misguided man, in many discourses have I not stated consciousness to be dependently arisen, since, without a condition, there is no origination of consciousness.

10
00:01:37,942 --> 00:01:40,626
But you, misguided man,

11
00:01:40,605 --> 00:01:48,495
have misrepresented us and by your wrong grasp and injured yourself and stored up much demerit.

12
00:01:50,597 --> 00:02:02,072
We are told that on hearing this, poor old Satie sat silent, dismayed, with shoulders drooping and head down, glum and without response.

13
00:02:05,635 --> 00:02:08,740
Now, I'd say we could all have sympathy with Satie.

14
00:02:09,866 --> 00:02:21,905
it certainly seems that our essence, call it consciousness, is that which speaks and feels and experiences, and that this essence has been with us all our life.

15
00:02:22,986 --> 00:02:34,183
And, if we believe in rebirth, it's hard to see what else within us might survive other than that which speaks and feels and experiences the results of good and bad karma.

16
00:02:36,006 --> 00:02:38,490
Obviously, we're badly mistaken here.

17
00:02:39,787 --> 00:02:43,091
we're suffering from the same delusion that got Sati into trouble.

18
00:02:45,973 --> 00:02:53,423
It is interesting that the Buddha gets Sati to explain his understanding before he so emphatically refutes this.

19
00:02:55,824 --> 00:03:02,453
This reflects the fact that we need to be clear about our delusions before we can see through them.

20
00:03:03,664 --> 00:03:11,731
We put them forward into the gaze of mindfulness, trusting that this will filter out the falsehood from the truth.

21
00:03:14,974 --> 00:03:17,717
The Buddha then reiterates his own teaching.

22
00:03:18,938 --> 00:03:22,962
Firstly, consciousness is of six kinds.

23
00:03:24,024 --> 00:03:32,912
For instance, if our eyes are open and there's a visible object in front of them, then eye consciousness can arise.

24
00:03:33,989 --> 00:03:41,860
If our hearing works okay and sound waves fall on the ears, then ear consciousness can arise.

25
00:03:43,423 --> 00:03:48,411
He gives the analogy of fire, a log fire, a grass fire.

26
00:03:49,431 --> 00:03:52,717
We name the fire depending on what fuel it is based upon.

27
00:03:56,723 --> 00:04:00,468
He then goes on to question the audience on three points.

28
00:04:01,444 --> 00:04:07,311
To start with, he asks whether they are clear that this has come to be.

29
00:04:07,390 --> 00:04:12,156
They all chorus in unison, yes, venerable sir.

30
00:04:12,216 --> 00:04:17,281
It is very irritating when we're scratching our heads wondering what on earth he means.

31
00:04:18,922 --> 00:04:26,490
But these short, often perplexing statements from the Buddha give us something to investigate in Vipassana.

32
00:04:27,853 --> 00:04:37,228
It would be worthwhile, when you next sit in meditation, to ask yourself whether your experience could be described by the phrase, This has come to be.

33
00:04:37,269 --> 00:04:53,035
Once our mind settles in meditation, we find ourselves in a sea of sensations and feelings, reactions of desire or aversion, emotions, thoughts and images.

34
00:04:54,786 --> 00:05:00,634
This can be incredibly confusing until we notice that only one of these is happening at any one time.

35
00:05:02,076 --> 00:05:09,064
It simplifies things to track each passing experience rather than try to make sense of the totality.

36
00:05:13,108 --> 00:05:15,973
Each experience could be labelled as this.

37
00:05:17,555 --> 00:05:18,935
We might be watching the breath.

38
00:05:19,838 --> 00:05:21,839
We feel glad to be watching the breath.

39
00:05:22,934 --> 00:05:27,639
What the Buddha is asking of us is to notice that gladness has come to be.

40
00:05:27,699 --> 00:05:32,607
After a while, we don't feel so glad anymore.

41
00:05:32,646 --> 00:05:37,252
We feel a bit glum, thinking something better should be happening.

42
00:05:38,355 --> 00:05:45,363
Again, what's asked of us is to notice that glumness has come to be, that discontent has come to be.

43
00:05:46,642 --> 00:05:53,713
In general, whatever takes our attention, we're being asked to notice that this is our present moment experience.

44
00:05:56,416 --> 00:06:07,132
To follow this to a deeper level, if our gaze lands on a green field, eye consciousness gives us an image of greenness.

45
00:06:08,529 --> 00:06:25,812
Concentration is rarely sharp enough to see individual moments of consciousness in this way, and so we see the world as a multitude of separate objects which all exist simultaneously, green fields and trees and sky and so on.

46
00:06:27,329 --> 00:06:45,490
But when we calm the mind enough to allow moments of deeper clarity, we see that only one sense contact can be registered at a time, for instance, greenness, blueness, greyness, and that we're building an overall picture by joining the dots.

47
00:06:47,139 --> 00:06:58,630
While it's an amazing feat of intelligence to be able to join the dots and negotiate the world based on the overall picture we get from this, we also need to see the underlying process.

48
00:06:59,994 --> 00:07:03,663
I had a glimpse of this one time as I was eating lunch on retreat.

49
00:07:04,285 --> 00:07:07,288
I saw the knife and fork moving slowly toward the potato.

50
00:07:08,369 --> 00:07:11,012
My attention was taken by something else for a moment.

51
00:07:11,653 --> 00:07:18,100
Then visual consciousness came to the fore again, only this time the knife and fork had moved closer to the potato.

52
00:07:19,100 --> 00:07:27,930
I realized I had just seen two visual stills within what I normally interpret as a continuous video of visual consciousness.

53
00:07:29,074 --> 00:07:33,261
Because of mindfulness, I wasn't joining the dots in the usual way.

54
00:07:34,141 --> 00:07:41,452
Instead, I knew that in between the two stills, I had no idea where the knife and fork were, or even whether they existed.

55
00:07:42,072 --> 00:07:45,098
There was a complete blank and absence of information.

56
00:07:46,059 --> 00:07:49,564
For those moments, visual consciousness had ceased.

57
00:07:51,687 --> 00:07:55,913
The Buddha never suggests that the world stops existing when we're not watching it.

58
00:07:56,673 --> 00:08:00,899
He doesn't attempt to describe reality in terms of objective science.

59
00:08:02,161 --> 00:08:07,708
What he describes is the cognitive process upon which we build our picture of reality.

60
00:08:09,069 --> 00:08:17,120
He wants us to see that our access to the world, our ability to know it consciously, is unstable, conditional.

61
00:08:18,096 --> 00:08:23,052
A portal opens, gives us a little snippet of information, then closes.

62
00:08:23,091 --> 00:08:29,170
As the Buddha teaches, consciousness arises and then ceases.

63
00:08:32,136 --> 00:08:52,126
Getting a direct experience of this undermines the delusion Sati describes so succinctly that there's just one consciousness that sees and feels and experiences the results of good and bad karma and that this same consciousness has been with us all our lives and will be with us the next life too.

64
00:08:54,149 --> 00:09:01,080
Sati's description mirrors our delusion but it doesn't bear scrutiny under the watchful eye of mindfulness.

65
00:09:04,081 --> 00:09:08,927
Seeing this stop-start nature of cognition is not simply academic.

66
00:09:10,230 --> 00:09:17,240
It might rock a person to the core of their being to realize how limited is our knowledge of reality.

67
00:09:19,082 --> 00:09:25,532
As we learn to live with this uncomfortable news, the inside gradually opens the heart.

68
00:09:26,524 --> 00:09:38,615
It helps us loosen our grip on certainties we cling to, entrenched opinions about who and what we are, how we should behave, how others should behave, etc.

69
00:09:39,476 --> 00:09:55,451
Knowing how little we actually know makes it easier to forgive mistakes, to be grateful that anything at all can actually work out right in the midst of such a paucity of real information dependent on so many unproven assumptions.

70
00:09:57,169 --> 00:10:05,525
we realize how much we're taking for granted and what a miracle it is even to be able to take a footstep or make a cup of tea.

71
00:10:09,538 --> 00:10:27,970
Having ascertained that his disciples understand experience from the viewpoint of present moment awareness, which can be summarized as, this has come to be, the Buddha then goes on to ask whether they're clear that its origination occurs with that as nutriment.

72
00:10:30,173 --> 00:10:34,179
Conscious experience depends on certain conditions.

73
00:10:34,918 --> 00:10:36,660
It doesn't arise from nowhere.

74
00:10:36,681 --> 00:10:39,666
It needs support, nutriment.

75
00:10:41,828 --> 00:10:45,634
All of these nutriments, he declares, have craving as their origin.

76
00:10:47,015 --> 00:10:51,522
Craving is another word for sensual desire or tanha in Pali.

77
00:10:52,504 --> 00:10:58,912
This, the Buddha had discovered, was the basic drive underlying all worldly experience.

78
00:10:58,932 --> 00:11:02,918
It's because we want something from the world that we become conscious of it.

79
00:11:04,315 --> 00:11:06,057
That's quite a thought to reflect on.

80
00:11:08,721 --> 00:11:12,928
Now of course the Buddha was conscious and could see and hear and think.

81
00:11:13,850 --> 00:11:16,173
He was living within the world of sense contact.

82
00:11:17,275 --> 00:11:21,162
So there's obviously a way to experience the world that doesn't depend on craving.

83
00:11:22,583 --> 00:11:25,369
The word for craving is tanha in Pali.

84
00:11:26,570 --> 00:11:28,212
It comes in three flavors.

85
00:11:29,289 --> 00:11:31,173
The desire for sense pleasure is one.

86
00:11:31,212 --> 00:11:35,902
Another is the desire to become, to be someone special.

87
00:11:37,244 --> 00:11:39,648
And finally the desire not to become.

88
00:11:40,929 --> 00:11:43,014
This is when we want to annihilate ourselves.

89
00:11:44,096 --> 00:11:53,172
In the extreme it means suicide, but in minor ways this desire arises out of embarrassment, for example, when we want to become invisible.

90
00:11:54,366 --> 00:11:59,583
Tana or craving refers to all of these three flavors of desire.

91
00:12:01,909 --> 00:12:06,356
There is a related word, chanda, which describes skillful desire.

92
00:12:07,378 --> 00:12:09,601
Chanda also supports consciousness.

93
00:12:10,543 --> 00:12:15,169
We see this when we use chanda to develop traits like metta, for example.

94
00:12:16,432 --> 00:12:19,417
We start spotting opportunities where goodwill is needed.

95
00:12:20,378 --> 00:12:22,640
We become more conscious of goodwill in others.

96
00:12:23,602 --> 00:12:30,312
It's like we've opened a door into a whole new aspect of life, an area we were previously not conscious of.

97
00:12:30,293 --> 00:12:36,818
The Buddha doesn't describe the workings of an enlightened being as we don't need to know this before we get there.

98
00:12:37,620 --> 00:12:43,686
But my guess is that Chanda plays a part in maintaining their consciousness within the phenomenal world.

99
00:12:44,606 --> 00:12:45,547
But that's an aside.

100
00:12:47,068 --> 00:12:56,638
What the Buddha is keen for us to understand is that within our unenlightened state all nutriment for conscious experience has craving as its base.

101
00:12:58,592 --> 00:13:12,131
Whatever is our present moment experience, this has come to be because we crave sense pleasure, we crave existence to become someone special, we crave non-existence to be invisible.

102
00:13:14,855 --> 00:13:26,052
The third question the Buddha puts to his disciples is whether they are clear that with the cessation of that nutriment, what has come to be is subject to cessation.

103
00:13:26,722 --> 00:13:30,268
Let's say what has come to be is a feeling of happiness.

104
00:13:31,450 --> 00:13:33,732
This will have been born from certain conditions.

105
00:13:34,474 --> 00:13:36,517
It could have been the thought of a job well done.

106
00:13:37,918 --> 00:13:45,250
If we can steady attention on the feeling, the thought will fade and sometime afterwards the feeling also fades.

107
00:13:46,510 --> 00:13:51,177
This shows us that the feeling of happiness needs certain supportive factors.

108
00:13:52,086 --> 00:13:57,753
In fact, everything we experience fades away after a few moments, once the supporting conditions give way.

109
00:13:58,994 --> 00:14:00,456
We see this in gross terms.

110
00:14:01,356 --> 00:14:02,738
An animal dies without food.

111
00:14:03,379 --> 00:14:04,860
A plant dies without water.

112
00:14:05,740 --> 00:14:07,523
Snow melts when it gets too warm.

113
00:14:08,224 --> 00:14:10,365
Machines break down when they're not maintained.

114
00:14:11,727 --> 00:14:19,596
Everything depends on its supporting conditions and fades away, ceases to exist once those conditions fail to appear.

115
00:14:22,798 --> 00:14:24,721
Mostly we hear this as bad news.

116
00:14:25,682 --> 00:14:27,164
We dread change and loss.

117
00:14:28,246 --> 00:14:31,030
But of course it can be used to suit our purposes.

118
00:14:32,513 --> 00:14:42,326
If we want to stop something undesirable, it's usually easier to undermine its supporting conditions than to tackle the problem head on.

119
00:14:43,623 --> 00:14:47,306
If a child is crying, we find out what is the problem.

120
00:14:48,067 --> 00:14:50,448
They might be hungry, so we give them something to eat.

121
00:14:51,649 --> 00:14:57,495
What we're doing is taking away the cause of their distress, rather than preventing them from crying.

122
00:14:59,197 --> 00:15:00,557
It's the same within us.

123
00:15:01,759 --> 00:15:04,621
We might sense anger as a big problem in our lives.

124
00:15:05,822 --> 00:15:13,629
Instead of trying to suppress every emotional flare-up, we can look for the causes of anger, work to undermine these.

125
00:15:15,095 --> 00:15:21,001
same for any of the hindrances, any unskilful tendencies we find within ourselves.

126
00:15:22,504 --> 00:15:28,131
The more we undermine the conditions, the more the unskilfulness loses its grip on us.

127
00:15:30,815 --> 00:15:35,000
This is essentially why the Buddha lists all the factors that support craving.

128
00:15:36,261 --> 00:15:41,928
The better we understand these, the more options we find for dismantling the whole structure.

129
00:15:44,812 --> 00:15:51,638
Having set the big picture, the Buddha then goes on to list the chain of factors that support craving.

130
00:15:53,179 --> 00:16:05,110
These are the first seven links in the chain known as dependent arising or dependent origination, a 12-link process that leads from ignorance to dukkha.

131
00:16:07,732 --> 00:16:14,058
The immediate support for craving, its proximate cause, is feeling, vedana in Pali.

132
00:16:15,169 --> 00:16:21,918
We crave to get more pleasant feelings, to get rid of unpleasant ones, to ignore neutral ones.

133
00:16:23,320 --> 00:16:25,302
What underlies feeling, he asks.

134
00:16:26,884 --> 00:16:29,748
The answer is sense contact.

135
00:16:31,370 --> 00:16:37,417
Feelings are generated only as a result of some snippet of information that has come through the senses.

136
00:16:39,299 --> 00:16:44,586
The feeling tells us whether this is pleasant, unpleasant or neutral.

137
00:16:46,321 --> 00:16:50,105
Feeling is a biological adaptation which aids survival.

138
00:16:51,166 --> 00:17:01,216
Any organism needs to be able to detect threats, to seek out food or other nourishment, to filter out sensory information that's not relevant to survival.

139
00:17:02,859 --> 00:17:11,468
So our biology is set up to filter sense contacts into these categories, giving us a feeling tone for each bit of sense data.

140
00:17:13,034 --> 00:17:18,461
The process happens so quickly, so automatically, we're rarely aware of our feelings.

141
00:17:18,863 --> 00:17:20,726
We simply react automatically.

142
00:17:21,787 --> 00:17:26,714
However, as the Buddha points out, feeling is the proximate cause for craving.

143
00:17:27,777 --> 00:17:31,643
And so we need to learn to tune into the feeling tone of experience.

144
00:17:35,008 --> 00:17:40,476
To recap on these three links, craving is based on feeling.

145
00:17:41,788 --> 00:17:46,015
When we experience a pleasant feeling, we crave for more of the same.

146
00:17:47,215 --> 00:17:50,942
When we experience an unpleasant feeling, we crave to get rid of it.

147
00:17:52,384 --> 00:17:54,707
We crave to ignore neutral feeling.

148
00:17:55,907 --> 00:18:03,077
In turn, feeling is only generated when a new bit of sensory information is registered by sense contact.

149
00:18:07,664 --> 00:18:10,107
What underlies sense contact?

150
00:18:11,101 --> 00:18:13,023
the six sense doors.

151
00:18:14,726 --> 00:18:19,153
One of these is forming the portal, allowing that snippet of information to come in.

152
00:18:20,934 --> 00:18:26,001
The sensation of warmth requires the body's tactile system as a door to consciousness.

153
00:18:27,163 --> 00:18:29,386
A bird song needs the hearing system.

154
00:18:30,769 --> 00:18:34,694
The thought of buttered toasts needs the mind as a sense door.

155
00:18:36,295 --> 00:18:46,625
When we acknowledge the crucial role of the sense doors, we also see that one way to reduce craving is to withdraw from as much sensory stimulation as possible.

156
00:18:47,787 --> 00:18:51,891
We go somewhere quiet, shut the eyes, make the body comfortable.

157
00:18:53,011 --> 00:18:59,759
With a bit of luck, the only challenging feelings we have to deal with are those that enter via the doorway of the mind.

158
00:19:02,622 --> 00:19:05,424
What underlies the six sense doors?

159
00:19:05,826 --> 00:19:07,229
mind and matter.

160
00:19:08,471 --> 00:19:09,633
Nama Rupa.

161
00:19:11,756 --> 00:19:21,410
The sense doors are built from the cells, blood, neurons in our bodies, animated by mental phenomena such as attention and intention.

162
00:19:24,855 --> 00:19:28,881
Nama Rupa translates literally as name and form.

163
00:19:29,856 --> 00:19:36,506
Form refers to the body, the world of matter, blood, bones, neurons.

164
00:19:38,368 --> 00:19:43,316
What gives this a name, a meaning, is nama, the mind.

165
00:19:46,779 --> 00:19:53,549
As an aside, it's generally understood the dependent arising describes how we experience the world.

166
00:19:54,391 --> 00:19:59,678
It's not a description of scientific reality, but of our inner cognitive reality.

167
00:20:00,738 --> 00:20:09,152
It's also generally understood that the first six of the links, up as far as sense contact, all occur simultaneously.

168
00:20:10,634 --> 00:20:20,171
It's not that we become aware of mind and matter, nama rupa, and then become aware of one of the sense bases and then the snippet of data from the outside world.

169
00:20:21,192 --> 00:20:25,799
Instead, we become conscious of all of these in the one moment.

170
00:20:26,944 --> 00:20:31,211
The usual way to say this is that they all arise simultaneously.

171
00:20:32,253 --> 00:20:42,952
We can't separate them in time, but we can examine our experience at any one time and tease out these various strands within the experience.

172
00:20:45,917 --> 00:20:51,567
Curiously, sense contact and feeling are also part of nāma.

173
00:20:53,084 --> 00:21:04,500
A simple mechanical understanding of dependent origination would suggest that since nama supports contact and feeling, it can't also contain them.

174
00:21:06,242 --> 00:21:09,387
But the reality in which we live isn't so simple.

175
00:21:10,990 --> 00:21:12,392
Think of an ecosystem.

176
00:21:13,637 --> 00:21:18,763
The top predators, let's say owls, depend on there being mice to prey upon.

177
00:21:19,664 --> 00:21:21,887
The mice depend on there being seeds to eat.

178
00:21:22,769 --> 00:21:25,311
The seeds depend on there being plants to develop them.

179
00:21:26,093 --> 00:21:27,734
The plants depend on the soil.

180
00:21:27,775 --> 00:21:32,400
The soil needs the nutriment from owl and moss droppings to be fertile.

181
00:21:34,122 --> 00:21:37,286
The dependence is intertwined rather than linear.

182
00:21:38,567 --> 00:21:40,809
Everything depends on everything else.

183
00:21:42,545 --> 00:21:50,195
If the owls disappear, the mouse population would explode, eating all the seeds, resulting in famine and devastation.

184
00:21:51,838 --> 00:21:57,807
So the owls, in one sense, support themselves, support the system by feeding off it.

185
00:22:00,632 --> 00:22:12,348
In the same way, contact and feeling support themselves because they are part of nama, the mental component underlying the sense bases.

186
00:22:15,906 --> 00:22:20,872
The sound that I'm hearing forms part of the mind that listens.

187
00:22:25,135 --> 00:22:34,806
Although the sound vibrations come from, for example, a bird singing, the sound I hear is internal and subjective.

188
00:22:36,607 --> 00:22:42,133
It's a purely mental phenomenon, an aspect of the mind that listens.

189
00:22:44,746 --> 00:22:49,492
Looked at from the point of view of experience, sound isn't external.

190
00:22:49,554 --> 00:22:53,759
It occurs within the mind, within consciousness.

191
00:22:56,443 --> 00:23:03,174
Similarly, the evaluation of the sound as pleasant, unpleasant or neutral is a mental process.

192
00:23:04,176 --> 00:23:10,145
It forms part of the mind that listens to the sound, feels it as pleasant.

193
00:23:14,480 --> 00:23:20,305
While this complexity might seem daunting we can use it to our advantage.

194
00:23:20,452 --> 00:23:25,039
For example, it helps to lessen our sense of separation from the world.

195
00:23:26,240 --> 00:23:33,432
If sounds are within me, forming part of my basic mentality, why not try to live more peacefully with them?

196
00:23:34,513 --> 00:23:47,051
If they sound pleasant to my ears, it evokes gratitude to reflect that the pleasant feeling is forming part of my mental make-up at this moment, helping me to see the world in a more positive way.

197
00:23:48,127 --> 00:24:00,788
If it's the grating noise from a jackhammer that I'm hearing, I'll have more compassion for myself when I reflect that the unpleasant feeling is coursing within me, affecting me at my core.

198
00:24:02,511 --> 00:24:12,127
If it's the background hum of the fridge I'm hearing, its evaluation in neutral tones forms part of the quietness in my own mental background.

199
00:24:12,529 --> 00:24:21,238
Noticing this invites me to time off from busyness and spend a few moments in refrigerator-hubbing meditation.

200
00:24:23,941 --> 00:24:41,777
What I'm saying, basically, is that knowing sense contact and feeling are in here, part of our subjective mental world, as opposed to out there, helps to draw attention inwards, steady the mind on these very sensations and the feelings they evoke.

201
00:24:44,338 --> 00:24:52,727
The more we can steady the mind, the more we foster positive qualities like mindfulness, compassion, gratitude, tranquility.

202
00:24:54,188 --> 00:25:01,934
At the same time, we're letting go of our usual urges towards reactivity, restlessness, doubt and other hindrances.

203
00:25:05,778 --> 00:25:14,346
The Buddha then asks what Nama Rupa depends on and answers that consciousness is their proximate cause.

204
00:25:15,794 --> 00:25:23,625
Consciousness, Vijnana in Pali, describes awareness at any one point of the six sense doors.

205
00:25:25,387 --> 00:25:28,413
A useful analogy is a mental screen.

206
00:25:30,075 --> 00:25:43,776
Consciousness is the screen itself, while sense contact, vedana and the other components of mind, such as attention and intention, are the images that appear on the screen.

207
00:25:45,645 --> 00:25:47,228
Imagine you're in a cinema.

208
00:25:48,609 --> 00:25:51,874
If the screen suddenly disappeared you wouldn't see the film.

209
00:25:53,276 --> 00:25:57,501
The light from the projector would pass on through, disappear into blackness.

210
00:25:58,803 --> 00:26:09,897
Similarly the ears could be ringing with the vibrations from a rock concert but because we're fast asleep the sounds disappear into the vast silence of unconsciousness.

211
00:26:14,282 --> 00:26:25,355
Although in this Sutta the Buddha describes consciousness as the condition upon which Nama Rupa rests in another Sutta the two are described as interdependent.

212
00:26:26,685 --> 00:26:32,893
Consciousness depends on Nama Rupa as much as Nama Rupa on consciousness.

213
00:26:34,294 --> 00:26:42,041
Sariputta, one of the Buddha's foremost disciples, gives the analogy of two sheaves of wheat resting against one another.

214
00:26:43,163 --> 00:26:45,566
If you take out one, the other collapses.

215
00:26:46,846 --> 00:26:49,670
Likewise for consciousness and Nama Rupa.

216
00:26:51,832 --> 00:26:56,237
The screen of consciousness is needed to play the film of Nama Rupa.

217
00:26:57,414 --> 00:27:03,644
The film contains mental factors like intention and attention which are needed to beget the screen.

218
00:27:05,627 --> 00:27:08,172
You could call it an eco-friendly screen.

219
00:27:09,354 --> 00:27:12,018
It only comes into being when there's a film to play.

220
00:27:13,019 --> 00:27:15,743
It decomposes instantly when it's not needed.

221
00:27:19,931 --> 00:27:24,417
The Buddha then asks, what is it that underlies consciousness?

222
00:27:26,508 --> 00:27:30,874
The answer is habitual formations .

223
00:27:31,054 --> 00:27:41,909
As the term suggests, these are the habits we develop as we repeat patterns of thought, speech and behaviour.

224
00:27:43,852 --> 00:27:48,278
A river cuts a channel through rock as it rushes from its source to the open sea.

225
00:27:49,480 --> 00:27:50,540
Similarly,

226
00:27:51,144 --> 00:28:01,718
As ignorance rushes toward dukkha, our thoughts, speech and actions cut out a sankhara, a channel through which our mental and physical energies can flow.

227
00:28:02,939 --> 00:28:15,094
The more often we repeat a pattern of thought, speech or action, the deeper that channel cuts, making it ever more likely that ignorance will choose that channel in order to flow to dukkha.

228
00:28:18,736 --> 00:28:21,380
Sankara comes in three categories.

229
00:28:23,363 --> 00:28:27,869
One relates to the mental formations of perception and feeling.

230
00:28:30,153 --> 00:28:33,499
We tend to see and feel the world in habitual ways.

231
00:28:35,121 --> 00:28:44,675
For example, we speak of people with a negative disposition, choosing fearful perceptions, detecting hostility in the most innocent remark.

232
00:28:45,719 --> 00:28:50,853
This is all stemming from a Sankara of unpleasant feeling, perceptions of danger.

233
00:28:50,913 --> 00:28:59,356
Others have an optimistic disposition, seeing the best in people and situations.

234
00:29:01,176 --> 00:29:06,443
Insofar as this is based on ignorance, what we're looking out for is worldly happiness.

235
00:29:07,325 --> 00:29:16,115
We see the best, not because of admiration or appreciation, but because we're used to feeding off the best that the world has to offer.

236
00:29:17,136 --> 00:29:23,724
When we walk into a party, we see the drinks counter, the food buffet, the most attractive people.

237
00:29:24,615 --> 00:29:32,963
A person with a negative disposition would have seen the messy, half-finished plates of food, heard insincerity in every peal of laughter.

238
00:29:34,526 --> 00:29:42,452
The deluded optimist usually manages to get the best out of situations, never notice the mess they're leaving for others to clear up.

239
00:29:44,976 --> 00:29:52,462
Then, there are those who habitually choose neutral feelings and the perceptions of indifference which support neutrality.

240
00:29:53,994 --> 00:29:58,623
when they walk into the room, they see neither the drinks cabinet nor the dirty plates.

241
00:29:59,205 --> 00:30:00,714
None of that matters very much.

242
00:30:01,942 --> 00:30:11,414
They might sidle into the first group that they see, accept whatever food and drink they're offered, play safe in conversation, quickly forgetting the names of whoever they're introduced to.

243
00:30:12,596 --> 00:30:17,742
The whole evening leaves only a vague impression on consciousness, makes little or no impact on their lives.

244
00:30:18,963 --> 00:30:25,992
Thus, the channel leading from ignorance to dukkha cuts a bit deeper, into the grove of neutrality and indifference.

245
00:30:29,145 --> 00:30:41,280
You might recognise these crude portraits of optimism, pessimism and indifference as the Buddhist description of the three personality types based on greed, hatred or delusion.

246
00:30:44,285 --> 00:30:54,698
It's interesting to reflect that underlying the will which drives us along roots of greed, hatred or delusion are habits of feelings and perception.

247
00:30:56,855 --> 00:31:08,405
It gets a bit mysterious here because Sankharas underlie consciousness and Nama Rupa, implying that they exist outside the world of mind and matter.

248
00:31:09,987 --> 00:31:18,875
Sankharas are bound up with another somewhat mysterious phenomenon in Buddhism, Kama.

249
00:31:18,895 --> 00:31:25,241
Kama and Sankhara are usually illustrated by analogy to seeds and fruit.

250
00:31:26,825 --> 00:31:38,301
Whatever desire we choose to act upon sows a seed of kama, which will later ripen as a fruit, a sankara, which prompts us to fulfill that desire again.

251
00:31:38,342 --> 00:31:51,481
While a seed and its fruit are directly linked in a material way, the link between our deeds and the sankara that result from them is immaterial.

252
00:31:52,761 --> 00:31:57,587
The Buddha warns us that the workings of Kama are beyond human understanding.

253
00:31:59,289 --> 00:32:15,951
Ultimately, Kama and Sankara lie in the realm of mystery, but one way to picture the link is to say that the doing of any deed results in a potential for its own repetition, a potential which underlies consciousness.

254
00:32:18,192 --> 00:32:20,234
We could use the analogy of a ghost.

255
00:32:21,236 --> 00:32:24,821
We are haunted by our past actions, speech and thoughts.

256
00:32:26,223 --> 00:32:28,046
But this isn't just a horror story.

257
00:32:29,147 --> 00:32:32,373
Many of these ghosts serve us well on the spiritual path.

258
00:32:33,213 --> 00:32:42,748
Thoughts, words and deeds stemming from wisdom and metta also want to impress themselves into consciousness and strengthen with each moment of mindfulness.

259
00:32:45,394 --> 00:33:05,444
So far we've been looking at the Sankhara of mental habits, the ghostly image of feelings and perceptions we've developed through favouring certain feelings and perceptions, the optimist favouring pleasant feelings, happy perceptions, the pessimist favouring unpleasant feeling, fearful or hostile perceptions and so on.

260
00:33:07,146 --> 00:33:16,446
Another variety of Sankara concerns verbal formations, our habits not only of speech but of directed thought and evaluation.

261
00:33:18,932 --> 00:33:21,337
Thoughts reflect how we conceive of the world.

262
00:33:22,599 --> 00:33:25,205
They rely on concepts, ideas.

263
00:33:25,877 --> 00:33:28,261
A baby doesn't think about what they're going to have for dinner.

264
00:33:28,461 --> 00:33:32,910
They just know when they're hungry and whether or not they like what's coming into their mouth.

265
00:33:34,051 --> 00:33:35,914
They live in immediate reality.

266
00:33:36,516 --> 00:33:45,692
Sensations, feelings, impulses of wanting and not wanting, simple perceptions like blueness, warmth, ease, unease.

267
00:33:45,672 --> 00:33:49,536
Gradually perceptions bundle together to reveal patterns.

268
00:33:50,458 --> 00:33:57,726
A lot of whiteness with some yellowness at one end turns into warm sweetness on the tongue and a filling of the belly.

269
00:33:59,067 --> 00:34:07,376
The concept of a feeding bottle starts to form as a very desirable pattern that is much more likely to happen if I cry loudly.

270
00:34:08,452 --> 00:34:20,447
And so we slowly learn how to manipulate the masses of sensory information that impinges on us each moment so as to get more of what makes us feel good and avoid what makes us feel bad.

271
00:34:20,507 --> 00:34:25,532
To manipulate the world like this, we need concepts.

272
00:34:26,472 --> 00:34:30,478
We need to stand back from immediate experience and make sense of it.

273
00:34:31,757 --> 00:34:36,302
we take a multitude of passing sensations and weave them into a concept.

274
00:34:36,943 --> 00:34:39,706
Feeding bottle, mummy, blanket.

275
00:34:41,027 --> 00:34:48,396
As we grow older, the level of abstraction increases so that we can think about governments, human rights, Buddhism.

276
00:34:49,818 --> 00:34:55,503
All of this mental activity happens when verbal sankhara underlie consciousness.

277
00:34:58,927 --> 00:35:10,083
The ability to abstract, to conceptualize, allows us make sense of our lives, choose a career, affect the world for good or evil, follow a spiritual path.

278
00:35:11,666 --> 00:35:14,251
We obviously don't want to destroy that ability.

279
00:35:15,492 --> 00:35:23,043
But we don't want to be enslaved by it either, unable to follow a single breath without spinning off into a steam of thought.

280
00:35:25,132 --> 00:35:33,807
We don't want to be forever haunted by the ghosts of our past thoughts, forever rehearsing what we'll say, repeating our opinions about this and that.

281
00:35:35,690 --> 00:35:49,875
We do this by sitting in meditation, again and again dropping the latest line of thought, choosing instead to let awareness dwell in that more immediate, non-conceptual reality of sensation and feeling.

282
00:35:52,606 --> 00:36:00,599
This is to strengthen the habitual formation in the third variety of Sankhara, bodily formations.

283
00:36:02,603 --> 00:36:10,818
These are our physical habits, the way we walk, our facial expression, our nervous twitches.

284
00:36:12,840 --> 00:36:17,449
As we sit in meditation, the most predominant habit is the breath.

285
00:36:18,643 --> 00:36:21,929
Breathing forms the basis for biological life.

286
00:36:22,891 --> 00:36:24,554
When we stop breathing, we die.

287
00:36:26,057 --> 00:36:32,690
Of course, other functions like heartbeat are also essential, but the breath is the one under voluntary control.

288
00:36:32,750 --> 00:36:38,661
It's a habit we initiate at birth and continually repeat until death.

289
00:36:41,070 --> 00:36:44,418
The Buddha places great emphasis on mindfulness of breathing.

290
00:36:45,639 --> 00:36:48,706
It's the first exercise in the Satipatthana Sutta.

291
00:36:50,550 --> 00:37:00,108
After a rains retreat, when a disciple asks him about his meditation, the Buddha responds that he spent most of the time being mindful of breathing.

292
00:37:02,992 --> 00:37:15,706
With three flavours of Sankara to choose between, verbal formations, mental formations and bodily formations, the Buddha chose the latter as the basis for consciousness during retreat.

293
00:37:17,507 --> 00:37:20,592
The Sankara of direct thought would have been unnecessary.

294
00:37:21,092 --> 00:37:22,873
He'd long since figured out the Dhamma.

295
00:37:23,635 --> 00:37:25,336
He didn't need to reflect on anything.

296
00:37:27,494 --> 00:37:37,409
The mental formation of pleasant feeling and perception would have allowed consciousness to establish itself in jhana, a very restful state of deep concentration.

297
00:37:39,092 --> 00:37:47,023
We might think he would choose to spend his retreat in the freedom of nibbana or one of those sublime states of jhana.

298
00:37:47,945 --> 00:37:55,577
But no, he deliberately chose to spend the months of the rains retreat being conscious of the in and out breath.

299
00:37:56,704 --> 00:37:57,465
Who knows why?

300
00:37:57,525 --> 00:38:04,436
My guess is that it strengthened his will to live to the ripe old age of 80.

301
00:38:05,938 --> 00:38:14,092
I like to think of him allowing the ghosts of his previous breaths draw the infinite wisdom of Nirvana into his human form.

302
00:38:16,576 --> 00:38:17,818
I'm speculating here.

303
00:38:19,773 --> 00:38:30,867
All we know is that the Buddha places great emphasis on the use of this Sankara to build mindfulness of breathing and that he chose to spend the months of the rains retreat doing this himself.

304
00:38:32,030 --> 00:38:40,762
So it's certainly a Sankara that can be used wisely and perhaps, who knows, is a way to strengthen our life energy, our will to live.

305
00:38:44,347 --> 00:38:48,092
The Buddha then asks what underlies Sankara.

306
00:38:50,266 --> 00:38:54,956
and answers that they are born and produced from ignorance.

307
00:38:58,385 --> 00:39:08,730
It's only because we don't fully understand how suffering is caused that we let sankaras come out of potential and into consciousness.

308
00:39:11,967 --> 00:39:13,949
Ignorance is our basic problem.

309
00:39:15,072 --> 00:39:20,101
The Buddha never lists anything else, original sin or whatever underlying ignorance.

310
00:39:21,603 --> 00:39:24,728
We eradicate ignorance by gaining wisdom.

311
00:39:27,452 --> 00:39:34,784
We gain wisdom by experiencing reality directly, not through the filters of conceptual thought.

312
00:39:36,824 --> 00:39:41,590
Mindfulness educates us as to the true nature of the world.

313
00:39:43,112 --> 00:39:52,224
Each up-close, touchy-feely encounter with experience shows that craving is feeding dissatisfaction, Dukkha.

314
00:39:55,168 --> 00:40:01,717
The deeper we let this truth sink in, the less we allow our Sankara ghost to haunt us.

315
00:40:03,418 --> 00:40:12,329
We learn to hold off till an inkling of wisdom becomes conscious, cutting out new pathways for our speech, actions and thoughts.

316
00:40:13,391 --> 00:40:23,284
Pathways that reflect the Dhamma, that take account of the fact that everything is in a constant process of creation and decay.

317
00:40:28,072 --> 00:40:38,646
Having followed the Buddha's analysis of our problem down to its base, ignorance, let's recap.

318
00:40:38,666 --> 00:40:56,831
To undermine delusion that Sati described so well, but I think we all have to admit to, the Buddha first asks us to drop below the level of conceptual thought and see experience as a series of happenings, a dynamic sequence of events.

319
00:40:58,297 --> 00:41:04,373
Secondly, he wants us to see that events are being continually nourished by craving.

320
00:41:05,717 --> 00:41:13,538
Ultimately, everything we experience on this side of enlightenment, anyhow, has craving as its source.

321
00:41:17,146 --> 00:41:25,394
The third thing he wants us to clarify is that things die away naturally once the supportive conditions are removed.

322
00:41:26,275 --> 00:41:27,416
This is good news.

323
00:41:28,438 --> 00:41:31,240
It means that we can put an end to our foolish craving.

324
00:41:32,623 --> 00:41:38,068
We don't have to tackle craving head on, stop ourselves desiring this or resisting that.

325
00:41:39,068 --> 00:41:44,335
Instead we can find out what conditions allow craving to come about in the first place.

326
00:41:45,157 --> 00:41:49,666
As we undermine these, craving dies out quite naturally.

327
00:41:51,690 --> 00:41:56,780
That's the point of teaching us about the chain of conditions underlying craving.

328
00:41:58,202 --> 00:42:06,559
The better we get to know these, the more skilled we get at removing the supportive structure within us that binds us to suffering.

329
00:42:08,934 --> 00:42:16,706
If you're looking for a very practical place to start, why not investigate the first point that the Buddha puts to his disciples?

330
00:42:19,068 --> 00:42:29,543
When the mind quietens in meditation, ask yourself whether your experience could be described by the phrase, this has come to be.

331
00:42:32,898 --> 00:42:39,195
May our practice liberate us from craving and bring us to the end of suffering.

